HEADWORD: Fad
<hw>Fad</hw> <pr>(f⟦acr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Faddle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A hobby ; freak;
whim.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is your favorite <qex>fad</qex> to draw plans.</q> <rj><qau>G.
Eliot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a practise followed enthusiastically by a number of
people for a limited period of time; <as>as, the latest <ex>fad</ex> in
fashion</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> craze; mania.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p> -- <wordforms><wf>Fad"dist</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
-- <wordforms><wf>Fad"dish</wf>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fadaise</ent>⟦br⟧
